extrainfo:This circuit is an Operational Transconductance Amplifier (OTA). It employs multiple NPN and PNP transistors to form a differential amplifier with current mirrors. The input differential pair consists of Q1 and Q2, and the output is taken at node io. Diodes D1 and D2 are connected between the input nodes vN and vP, and VA. The circuit is powered by VCC and VEE.

FIGURE 5.42 Operational transconductance amplifier (OTA).
where $I$ is the current provided by the user to bias the $Q_{1}-Q_{2}$ pair. The plot of $i_{0}$ versus the difference $v_{P}-v_{N}$ forms the familiar $s$-shaped curve seen in Fig. 4.44. This curve is nonlinear, but if we limit the input voltage to the range $\left|v_{P}-v_{N}\right| \ll 4 V_{T}$ (approximately 100 mV), the small-signal approximation allows us to retain only the first term in the series expansion $\tanh x=x-x^{3}/3+\cdots$ and write

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{o}=\frac{I}{2 V_{T}}\left(v_{p}-v_{n}\right) \tag{5.72}
\end{equation*}
$$

Several key observations can be made:

- In small-signal operation, the transconductance gain

$$
\begin{equation*}
G_{m}=\frac{i_{o}}{v_{p}-v_{n}}=\frac{I}{2 V_{T}} \tag{5.73}
\end{equation*}
$$

is directly proportional to the bias current $I$, allowing it to be externally programmed by the user. Indeed, bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) can easily accommodate current ranges spanning more than five decades (>100 dB), making OTAs highly suitable for a variety of programmable circuits, such as programmable amplifiers, oscillators, and filters, particularly in wide-dynamic range applications like audio and electronic music.
