The versatility of the transconductor can be significantly improved by configuring it to respond to differential inputs. In the widely used configuration shown in Fig. 5.42, known as the operational transconductance amplifier (OTA), this capability is realized through the differential pair $Q_{1}-Q_{2}$. To achieve a high common-mode rejection ratio (CMRR), this pair is biased using the high-output-resistance Wilson mirror $Q_{3}-Q_{4}-Q_{5}$. The current of $Q_{2}$ is replicated and directed to the output node by the Wilson mirror $Q_{9}-Q_{10}-Q_{11}$, while $Q_{1}$'s current is first mirrored by $Q_{6}-Q_{7}-Q_{8}$ and then conveyed to the output node by the mirror $Q_{12}-Q_{13}-Q_{14}$, where it is subtracted from the current delivered by $Q_{9}-Q_{10}-Q_{11}$. Temporarily disregarding the diodes $D_{1}$ and $D_{2}$, we adapt Eq. (4.73) to express

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{o}=i_{C 11}-i_{C 12}=i_{C 2}-i_{C 1}=I \times \tanh \left(\frac{v_{P}-v_{N}}{2 V_{T}}\right) \tag{5.71}
\end{equation*}
$$

