- Both inputs are large-signal types. When $v_{X}$ and $v_{Y}$ share the same polarity, the cell outputs $i_{O1} - i_{O2} = I - 0 = I$, whereas when $v_{X}$ and $v_{Y}$ have opposite polarities, it outputs $i_{O1} - i_{O2} = 0 - I = -I$. This function resembles the exclusive-or function in digital circuits. In this capacity, the cell serves as a phase detector in phase-locked loop systems.

Similar to OTAs, the small-signal constraint can be a significant limitation in certain multiplier applications, necessitating provisions to accommodate larger input magnitudes while ensuring accurate multiplication. Fig. 5.46 presents a popular Gilbert Cell application that meets these requirements. Key observations include:

- The $Q_{5}-Q_{6}$ pair employs emitter degeneration via $R_{Y}$ to expand its input signal range by the desired amount. Ignoring base currents, we apply KCL, Ohm's law, and KVL to derive:

$$
\begin{aligned}
i_{C5} - i_{C6} & = \left(I_{Y} + \frac{v_{E5} - v_{E6}}{R_{Y}}\right) - \left(I_{Y} + \frac{v_{E6} - v_{E5}}{R_{Y}}\right) = 2 \frac{v_{E5} - v_{E6}}{R_{Y}} \\
& = \frac{\left(v_{Y1} - v_{BE5}\right) - \left(v_{Y2} - v_{BE6}\right)}{0.5 R_{Y}}
\end{aligned}
$$

